You do it all the time in web apps. For example, changing the text of a toggle link between &quot;show&quot; and &quot;hide.&quot; For example, with jQuery:<p><pre><code>  $(&#x27;#toggleLink&#x27;).click(function() {
    if ($(&#x27;#toggleLink&#x27;).html() == &#x27;Show&#x27;) {
      showRollout();
      $(&#x27;#toggleLink&#x27;).html(&#x27;Hide&#x27;);
    } else {
      hideRollout();
      $(&#x27;#toggleLink&#x27;).html(&#x27;Show&#x27;);
    ]
  });</code></pre>

This is awesome! I went to UConn, so I&#x27;ll obviously hard-code a UConn win there. But I heard on NPR today that, historically, a 12 seed has a 50% chance of upsetting a 5 seed in the first round. If I&#x27;m biasing towards the higher seeds everywhere else, that means my code looks like this:<p>function (game, team1, team2) {<p><pre><code>  var winner_team = &quot;Connecticut&quot;;

  if (team1.name == winner_team) {
    team1.winsGame();
  } else if (team2.name == winner_team) {
    team2.winsGame();
  } else if (team1.seed > team2.seed) {
    team2.winsGame();
  } else if (team2.seed == &quot;12&quot;) {
    team2.winsGame();
  } else {
    team1.winsGame();
  }

}</code></pre>

Modified to also record the elapsed times:<p><pre><code>  # from https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=7411120
  export NOW_FORMAT=&#x27;%F %T&#x27;
  export NOW_FORMAT2=&#x27;+%Y-%m-%d %H:%M:%S&#x27;
  export NOW_FILE=&quot;$HOME/.now&quot;
  now() {
    if [ -e $NOW_FILE ] &&
       last_line=$(tail -n1 $NOW_FILE | cut -d &quot; &quot; -f 1,2) &&
       time0=$(date -j -f &quot;$NOW_FORMAT&quot; &quot;$(tail -n1 $NOW_FILE)&quot; &quot;+%s&quot;) && 
       time1=$(date -j &quot;+%s&quot;)
    then echo &quot;ET $(( $time1 - $time0 ))&quot; >> $NOW_FILE
    fi
    echo $(date +&quot;$NOW_FORMAT&quot;) - &quot;$@&quot; >> $NOW_FILE
    tail $HOME/.now # show the last few lines
  }</code></pre>
